{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492452"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:30:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:30:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1069"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1069"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.29,0.04,0.46,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1069"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79749"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1069"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1069"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65053"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1836"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41101"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79749"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of worsening pain. He has inoperable pancreatic cancer with an estimated prognosis of four months. He has no other significant medical history. His medications include slow-release morphine 60 mg twice daily, immediate-release morphine 2-hourly as needed, and methadone 5 mg twice daily. He previously trialled pregabalin and dexamethasone without benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable but alert. His vital signs are within normal limits. He reports constant epigastric pain radiating to his back that disrupts his sleep. He requires breakthrough morphine doses every 1-2 hours with inadequate pain control. The morphine causes significant drowsiness, interfering with his goal of meaningful family interaction. He is managing activities of daily living with family support and tolerates a soft diet.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in pain management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase slow-release morphine frequency to three times daily","Add fentanyl patches","Trial pregabalin at a lower dose","Perform coeliac plexus block","Increase immediate-release morphine frequency"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with poorly controlled pancreatic cancer pain despite escalating opioid doses, with side effects impacting his quality of life. The key consideration is finding a management strategy that aligns with his goals of maintaining alertness for family interaction while achieving adequate pain control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoeliac plexus block\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it provides effective pain relief while minimising systemic side effects. This procedure involves neurolytic blockade of the coeliac plexus, which carries pain fibres from the pancreas. Evidence from systematic reviews supports its use in pancreatic cancer for improved pain control with fewer adverse effects compared to opioid therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing slow-release morphine\u003C/strong\u003E frequency would likely worsen his drowsiness without necessarily improving pain control, given that he is already experiencing significant side effects at the current dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdding fentanyl patches\u003C/strong\u003E would further increase his total opioid load, potentially exacerbating side effects without addressing the underlying mechanism of pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing immediate-release morphine\u003C/strong\u003E frequency would not address his constant pain pattern and would likely worsen his drowsiness, conflicting with his goals of care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrial pregabalin at a lower dose\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be beneficial given his previous poor response and side effects at a higher dose.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Coeliac plexus block provides effective pain relief with minimal side effects in pancreatic cancer.","Pain management in palliative care should align with the patient\u0027s goals of care and preferences regarding side effects.","Increasing opioid doses may worsen side effects without providing adequate pain control in pancreatic cancer."],"references":["Arcidiacono PG, Calori G, Carrara S, et al. Celiac plexus block for pancreatic cancer pain in adults. Cochrane Database Syst Rev 2011; :CD007519. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21412903/","Wyse JM, Carone M, Paquin SC, et al. Randomized, double-blind, controlled trial of early endoscopic ultrasound-guided celiac plexus neurolysis to prevent pain progression in patients with newly diagnosed, painful, inoperable pancreatic cancer. J Clin Oncol. 2011;29:3541. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21844506/","Pain Management Principles in Palliative Care. In: eTG complete [Online]. 2016 [updated 2020, cited 2021 Feb 25]. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/index#toc_d1e47","Wood H, Dickman A, Star A, Boland JW. Updates in palliative care \u2013 overview and recent advancements in the pharmacological management of cancer pain. Clin Med (Lond). 2018;18(1):17. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29436434/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65053"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1069"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65053"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T14:24:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-23T20:55:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1069"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79749"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/